"{\"content\":{\"body\":\"> The coordination and data consistency between shards requires extremely careful protocol design to make the whole system secure and stable. There are also significantly more corner cases to consider which don’t exist in a non-sharded blockchain, mostly thanks to new elements such as crosslinks, cross-shard transactions and resharding. Eth 2.0 needs to build all these on top of the legacy Eth 1.0, which brings additional compatibility issues into the picture.”\\n\\n***Related: [Ethereum Developers Roll Up Their Sleeves in Hunt for Scalability Cure](https://cointelegraph.com/news/ethereum-developers-roll-up-their-sleeves-in-hunt-for-scalability-cure)***\\n\\nSince it is the clients who are responsible for storing the data on a blockchain and validating blocks, it is important that they are fully synchronized. Most of the seven individual clients currently under development for Ethereum 2.0 are working on optimizing Schlesi — the first Ethereum 2.0 multi-client test network that simulates the core network environment. After successful trials of Schlesi, Ethereum developers decided to move forward with the launch of a more formal test network, with several clients scheduled for June 2020.\",\"timestamp\":1639035361,\"title\":\"The coordination and data consistency between\"},\"digest\":\"6yxYcdPTqQ5T2SSzNiZr6RuP_jL0Azy2l9m4iwUvIQ0\",\"authorship\":{\"contributor\":\"0xcd17565e77B8DF79252E1682B4E2F7ebA87A13eE\",\"signingKey\":\"{\\\"crv\\\":\\\"P-256\\\",\\\"ext\\\":true,\\\"key_ops\\\":[\\\"verify\\\"],\\\"kty\\\":\\\"EC\\\",\\\"x\\\":\\\"K0VzJsVlSsZ6Cr9dmt7iKPLddaZ37pNOsbXJfdS1lIY\\\",\\\"y\\\":\\\"be3yiGk9wd7dbAbTA8fY3hHtfrYRr9VMRGc1InrIV1w\\\"}\",\"signature\":\"nIy504ExmyyF1qs3peNcCLYmUwS3adiwfAgY2y2lK3-9IcJ7iAMcQlnDrdkM0K1wObRmyq_EWmy--enhEy7txA\",\"signingKeySignature\":\"0x40baf2e93371e5796ef21145e68a9f6c5c5dfbeeee836baf22043c8afc3cb28b570cea2e6e06acd594c5c199d59f714c2aedaae9688462d460f52ae3639ee1981b\",\"signingKeyMessage\":\"I author